AB  - When the Norwegian sea captain Magnus Andersen reflected back in his published account of his endeavor to reconstruct a ninth-century Viking longship and sail it to the United States to perform at the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago two years earlier, he concluded that one thing alone had made the effort worth it: his countrymen, the Norwegian immigrants in America, transcended the inferior position of belonging to a "small and unknown nation" and for a moment enjoyed the limelight on the world stage. "It is difficult for an immigrant or settler in a foreign land to make a living," he wrote, "when he meets prejudice on account of his nationality" Performing belonging has been a key component of the relatively recent fields of both experimental archaeology and performance as research. This essay investigates a modern instantiation of this type of historical belonging: the journey of the reconstructed Norse vessel Viking at the world's fair in 1893. Here, in perhaps the first-ever effort in experimental archaeology and performance as research, the re-performance of the past played out in a transatlantic world of cultural contacts, exchanges, and migrations. Despite Andersen's claims that the project was all about Norwegian Americans, the story of a Viking ship traversing the ocean also became not only a self-conscious articulation for Norwegian independence from Sweden, but was also seized on by the Protestant East Coast elites of the United States, who, in fear of decline, could find in it a counter-narrative to the story that Christopher Columbus had discovered America.
